x4freetext: The Separate Sector Cyclotron at
iThemba LABS, Somerset West, South Africa.
The compact cyclotron CV 28 and the
and the injector cyclotron of COSY at FZJ, Germany.
All experiments were done using the
activation technique whereby stacks of samples were
prepared. Each stack generally contained four to
seven samples in addition to Al and Cu absorber
foils inserted for energy adjustment.
The beam intensity varied between 80 and 100 nA.
+ as well as via a Faraday cup installed in the
irradiation chamber of iThemba LABS.
At iThemba LABS, Ge metal foils (99.999% pure) of
250 mm thickness were irradiated.
At Forschungszentrum Julich, GeO2 of natural isotopic
composition (99.999% pure) was used.
In order to obtain thin targets for irradiation,
layers of finely powdered GeO2 were prepared via the
sedimentation technique.
The powder was sedimented on a 0.1mm thick aluminium
backing and covered with 0.01mm thick Al foil. This
way, layers could be obtained with natGe contents of
High-resolution HPGe detectors. The detector
efficiency was determined using calibrated standard
sources from PTB Braunschweig and Amersham Internat.
The mean uncertainty of the primary
proton energy
Weighing 1%
Uniformity of the sample 5%
The individual uncertainties considered in
the measurements are included:
(ERR-1) Weighing 1%
(ERR-2) Uniformity of the sample 5%
* Detector efficiency 3-4%
* Counting statistics 1-2%
* Peak area analysis 2-3%
* Beam current 6-11%
* Decay data 0.1-1%
The uncertainty due to real coincidence was negligible
due to the large distance (410 cm) between each sample
and the detector.
The total uncertainty was calculated with error
propagation according to Gauss.
